<section xml:id="Glide-Glide">
    <title>Glide Glide</title>
    
<ol>

<li><p>In this figure below, <m>\triangle ABC</m> has been rotated once around point A, and again around point B. Do you think we can get from the left triangle to the right triangle in a single rigid motion?</p>
            <example>
            <figure xml:id="glide_glide-1">
<image source="https://raw.githubusercontent.com/nickdowdall/Trans-geo/master/rigid_motions/other-stuff/pictures/new-pictures/glide_glide-1.png" width="90%"/>
<caption><m>\triangle ABC</m> and it's double rotation</caption>
           </figure>
           </example>
</li>

<li><p>Perhaps you have come to the conclusion that it is a single rotation. How would one go about finding the rotation's center?</p>
			<example>
            <figure xml:id="glide_glide-2">
<image source="https://raw.githubusercontent.com/nickdowdall/Trans-geo/master/rigid_motions/other-stuff/pictures/new-pictures/glide_glide-2.png" width="90%"/>
<caption><m>\triangle ABC</m> and it's double rotation</caption>
           </figure>
           <hint><p>If <m>B</m> and <m>B''''</m> is a single rotation, that would mean that they lie on the same circle. What would that mean about the distance from the center of the circle to <m>B</m> and <m>B''''</m>?</p></hint>
           </example>
</li>

<li><p>Because points on a circle are all the same distance from the center of the circle (definition of radius), then if point <m>O</m> is the center of the circle, then <m>\overline{OB} = \overline{OB''''}</m>.</p>
<example>
            <figure xml:id="glide_glide-3">
<image source="https://raw.githubusercontent.com/nickdowdall/Trans-geo/master/rigid_motions/other-stuff/pictures/new-pictures/glide_glide-3.png" width="90%"/>
<caption><m>\triangle ABC</m> and it's rotation</caption>
           </figure>
           <hint><p>If <m>\overline{OB} = \overline{OB''''}</m>, then O lies on the perpendicular bisector of <m>QB''''</m>.</p></hint>
           </example>
</li>

